<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The FDA's earlier attempts to regulate ephedra, starting in
1997, were beaten down by political opposition and criticism that
the agency failed to scientifically prove the substance was unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   With drugs, manufacturers are required to show the products are
safe before putting them on the market. But with dietary
supplements, which are regulated like foods, federal law places the
burden on the FDA to prove the product is unsafe, before it can
impose restrictions.
</P>
<P>
   Citing adverse reaction reports collected by the agency, the FDA
originally proposed requiring companies to sell ephedra products
only in low dosages and to advise consumers to use them for no more
than seven days. The proposal also would have banned popular
products that mix ephedra with caffeine _ a combination that
medical experts say greatly magnifies stimulant effects.
</P>
<P>
   But the FDA backed off the proposal, after an uproar from
industry leaders and some members of Congress and a report from the
General Accounting Office criticizing the agency's methodology for
proving ephedra was unsafe.
</P>
<P>
   In its Feb. 25 letter to Congress, the agency withdrew its
earlier proposal to limit ephedra dosages and announced it will
hold hearings to work out new ways to handle the safety concerns
about the substance.
</P>
